00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:23.060
So it's an interesting device.

00:09:23.060 --> 00:09:25.210
Again, all of the new devices
are not necessarily going to

00:09:25.210 --> 00:09:27.680
have that issue, but they are
going to definitely have

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:31.457
issues because we're moving
towards unified models here in

00:09:31.457 --> 00:09:33.060
mobile-- which is exciting.

00:09:33.060 --> 00:09:35.670
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, it
is really cool.

00:09:35.670 --> 00:09:39.500
I mean, I don't know if I'd
characterize it as being

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:41.970
because of unified shaders.

00:09:41.970 --> 00:09:45.240
I think it just happened to
come along with that.

00:09:45.240 --> 00:09:46.930
It's a little cold in here.

00:09:46.930 --> 00:09:49.010
OK, actually I just wanted
to cover up my man boobs.

00:09:49.010 --> 00:09:50.460
DAN GALPIN: No, I totally,
totally get that.

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:51.810
[INAUDIBLE].

00:09:51.810 --> 00:09:56.980
So let's talk a little bit
about the game behind us.

00:09:56.980 --> 00:09:58.710
Because it is here, and the
people are sort of wanting--

00:09:58.710 --> 00:10:00.440
so this is "Greedy Spiders 2."

00:10:00.440 --> 00:10:01.870
IAN NI-LEWIS: So I remember--
"Greedy Spiders," didn't we

00:10:01.870 --> 00:10:04.720
play that and it was sort
of a puzzle game, right?

00:10:04.720 --> 00:10:05.840
DAN GALPIN: It is
a puzzle game.

00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:07.830
IAN NI-LEWIS: You had to
move your flies or

00:10:07.830 --> 00:10:08.250
something like that.

00:10:08.250 --> 00:10:09.990
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, so the goal
with this one is to--

00:10:09.990 --> 00:10:11.485
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh,
this is cute.

00:10:11.485 --> 00:10:14.790
DAN GALPIN: --is to free your
flies from the spiders.

00:10:14.790 --> 00:10:18.980
And it's actually fairly
tricky to do that.

00:10:21.930 --> 00:10:25.270
The spider will always follow
the path towards the nearest

00:10:25.270 --> 00:10:28.810
bug in terms of the numbers
of segments.

00:10:28.810 --> 00:10:30.970
And so you can use
that against him.

00:10:30.970 --> 00:10:35.786
So as you see here, the goal is
now to isolate him from all

00:10:35.786 --> 00:10:38.505
of the other bugs as quickly
as possible.

00:10:38.505 --> 00:10:40.240
And that's how we get
the best score.

00:10:40.240 --> 00:10:44.770
And then once he's isolate, the
bugs will get to go free.

00:10:44.770 --> 00:10:47.950
And there's all sorts of stuff
the game starts throwing at

00:10:47.950 --> 00:10:48.900
you in addition.

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:51.110
So the first one is cutting,
you can freeze them.

00:10:51.110 --> 00:10:53.910
There's also other stuff you can
do to the spider in order

00:10:53.910 --> 00:10:56.990
to prevent it from
eating the bugs.

00:10:56.990 --> 00:10:58.920
And I think it's a really
clever game.

00:10:58.920 --> 00:11:00.130
The puzzles get really, really

00:11:00.130 --> 00:11:02.160
challenging as it goes through.

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:04.970
This is an example of a game
that's done very, very well.

00:11:04.970 --> 00:11:07.100
The back key, you see, does not
do anything here, which is

00:11:07.100 --> 00:11:07.950
unfortunate.

00:11:07.950 --> 00:11:11.140
It actually should technically
do something--

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:12.520
but nothing.

00:11:12.520 --> 00:11:14.170
IAN NI-LEWIS: You're watching
the confidence monitor, right,

00:11:14.170 --> 00:11:16.190
so you have an idea of what
people can and can't see?

00:11:16.190 --> 00:11:20.440
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, so I'm pushing
the back key here.

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:23.130
You can actually see the outline
of the tablet here.

00:11:23.130 --> 00:11:24.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: No, no it's OK.

00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:24.850
It's OK.

00:11:24.850 --> 00:11:26.900
Here, I'll show you
how we do this.

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:27.780
DAN GALPIN: Oh yeah?

00:11:27.780 --> 00:11:31.600
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, we
just move your chair.

00:11:31.600 --> 00:11:32.640
As you can see--

00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:33.530
DAN GALPIN: As you can see--

00:11:33.530 --> 00:11:35.020
IAN NI-LEWIS: --there are
stars in this game.

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:37.280
DAN GALPIN: Yes.

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:38.990
This is great, actually.

00:11:38.990 --> 00:11:43.140
One of us can actually play the
role of the letter turner,

00:11:43.140 --> 00:11:43.900
the Vanna White role.

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:44.020
IAN NI-LEWIS: No,
you know what?

00:11:44.020 --> 00:11:48.300
I'll tell you exactly why I
wanted to set up this way.

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:51.745
Because I'm just goddamn sick of
talking about the back key.

00:11:51.745 --> 00:11:54.750
Plus actually, there
was that hater.

00:11:54.750 --> 00:11:56.240
DAN GALPIN: Was there a hater?

00:11:56.240 --> 00:11:57.820
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, not
on our show, but on

00:11:57.820 --> 00:11:59.750
me and Reto's show.

00:11:59.750 --> 00:12:01.080
The guy went off, he's
like, man don't

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:01.690
listen to those guys.

00:12:01.690 --> 00:12:02.820
They probably work for Apple.

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:06.080
They're trying to
ruin Android.

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:07.700
DAN GALPIN: Dude, really?

00:12:07.700 --> 00:12:09.800
Look, no one from Apple
would wear this hat.

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:10.720
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, I
guess that's true.

00:12:10.720 --> 00:12:12.350
Well, you know what was actually
really hilarious,

00:12:12.350 --> 00:12:16.500
though, was one of the things
he said was, I can't believe

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:21.540
you're telling people not to
have an exit dialogue before

00:12:21.540 --> 00:12:25.560
you back out of the application
because every

00:12:25.560 --> 00:12:26.740
application should have that.

00:12:26.740 --> 00:12:28.220
What if it takes a long
time to reload?

00:12:28.220 --> 00:12:29.730
And I'm like, that's a
really good point.

00:12:29.730 --> 00:12:34.990
But really, the only apps that
get a pass on that are games

00:12:34.990 --> 00:12:38.810
because yes, games can take a
while to reload on earlier

00:12:38.810 --> 00:12:42.000
systems or if you're under
tremendous memory pressure.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:42.780
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:47.120
In general, if you really want
to throw a dialogue up because

00:12:47.120 --> 00:12:50.880
of loading, it's OK but in
general, it's better to just

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:51.750
not do it at all.

00:12:51.750 --> 00:12:55.000
I'm still of the mindset
that user will

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.240
figure out fairly quickly--

00:12:57.240 --> 00:13:01.470
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, now that
you don't lose your context

00:13:01.470 --> 00:13:03.970
when you lose focus,
then I think that

00:13:03.970 --> 00:13:04.780
that's absolutely right.

00:13:04.780 --> 00:13:08.020
Because the user is either going
to go right back to the

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:10.940
game, in which case you should
still have your context and

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:13.150
you should still have
everything.

00:13:13.150 --> 00:13:17.350
Basically you should pause and
then just let them resume.

00:13:17.350 --> 00:13:22.550
Or the user doesn't care anymore
and your game will get

00:13:22.550 --> 00:13:23.170
killed off.

00:13:23.170 --> 00:13:25.500
And as long as you handle the
notifications correctly,

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:26.530
you're probably going
to be fine.

00:13:26.530 --> 00:13:27.450
DAN GALPIN: Well, you know,
we're so happy.

00:13:27.450 --> 00:13:29.680
This game actually does
not have a menu key.

00:13:29.680 --> 00:13:30.790
It's doing a lot of
things right.

00:13:30.790 --> 00:13:33.440
But I'm sitting here
and I have to--

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:35.435
OK, first of all, this
is something

00:13:35.435 --> 00:13:36.640
weird about these games.

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:40.090
I have the bricks, and the
bricks say I'm actually going

00:13:40.090 --> 00:13:42.190
back to this other menu that
looks like bricks.

00:13:42.190 --> 00:13:43.320
And then we've got an on-screen
back key here.

00:13:43.320 --> 00:13:43.930
IAN NI-LEWIS: Wait, wait.

00:13:43.930 --> 00:13:44.655
Oh, yeah.

00:13:44.655 --> 00:13:45.390
Yeah.

00:13:45.390 --> 00:13:46.715
DAN GALPIN: But that
back key does work.

00:13:46.715 --> 00:13:47.800
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's a
little unfortunate.

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:49.410
Can you swipe?

00:13:49.410 --> 00:13:50.030
DAN GALPIN: You can.

00:13:50.030 --> 00:13:50.620
You can swipe.

00:13:50.620 --> 00:13:51.670
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well,
it's a different--

00:13:51.670 --> 00:13:55.390
DAN GALPIN: It's not a proper
swiping motion, but it is--

00:13:55.390 --> 00:13:59.400
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, that's one
thing, by the way, that I've

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:00.820
noticed on a couple of games.

00:14:00.820 --> 00:14:02.130
They'll implement a swipe,
but they won't

00:14:02.130 --> 00:14:03.510
implement it with physics.

00:14:03.510 --> 00:14:06.910
And as you get on to bigger
devices, it's really annoying

00:14:06.910 --> 00:14:09.440
because you have to drag your
whole finger all the way

00:14:09.440 --> 00:14:10.100
across the devices.

00:14:10.100 --> 00:14:12.130
DAN GALPIN: It's particularly
nice if you can use the

00:14:12.130 --> 00:14:13.990
physics that's built
into Android in

00:14:13.990 --> 00:14:16.960
terms of gesture detector.

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:20.520
It makes the game feel like an
Android game, and it makes it

00:14:20.520 --> 00:14:22.590
feel a little bit customized
for that device.

00:14:22.590 --> 00:14:23.850
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, yeah.

00:14:23.850 --> 00:14:24.290
Exactly.

00:14:24.290 --> 00:14:28.940
Because the gesture detector and
the flywheel physics will

00:14:28.940 --> 00:14:35.600
in general do the right
thing as far as the

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:38.160
momentum of your swipe.

00:14:38.160 --> 00:14:40.610
And people are going
to be used to that.

00:14:40.610 --> 00:14:42.430
Because all these other
apps use it.

00:14:42.430 --> 00:14:46.470
So if you tune it so that you
really, really like it and

00:14:46.470 --> 00:14:50.260
it's different from the system
default, you might want to

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:53.550
just ask yourself why
you did that.

00:14:53.550 --> 00:14:54.920
DAN GALPIN: Well, it is really
funny because there's a lot of

00:14:54.920 --> 00:14:56.740
games that actually have
tried to tune this.

00:14:56.740 --> 00:14:58.760
And you really notice it.

00:14:58.760 --> 00:15:00.770
It's a visceral quality.

00:15:00.770 --> 00:15:02.890
The game feels thick
or sticky.

00:15:02.890 --> 00:15:06.820
And what we find is that our
physics are a little looser

00:15:06.820 --> 00:15:10.040
than some other touch-based
operating systems, especially

00:15:10.040 --> 00:15:11.290
in the newer versions.

00:15:11.290 --> 00:15:13.970
We really wanted to have this
very active and alive and

00:15:13.970 --> 00:15:16.200
elastic feel to the
user interface.

00:15:16.200 --> 00:15:18.230
And so when you have a game
that's using it, it feels

00:15:18.230 --> 00:15:22.770
like, ugh, I'm going through
this sludge trying to get

00:15:22.770 --> 00:15:23.410
through the UI.

00:15:23.410 --> 00:15:25.470
So in general, I think
it's a great idea.

00:15:25.470 --> 00:15:26.160
IAN NI-LEWIS: There
is one really bad

00:15:26.160 --> 00:15:27.630
thing about it, though.

00:15:27.630 --> 00:15:32.600
And actually, look it up
in the ViewPager code.

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:35.790
There is a fudge factor that we
apply to our own physics,

00:15:35.790 --> 00:15:37.325
like a factor of four.

00:15:37.325 --> 00:15:38.150
DAN GALPIN: It's true.

00:15:38.150 --> 00:15:39.592
IAN NI-LEWIS: Because we suck.

00:15:39.592 --> 00:15:42.260
But whatever.

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:44.260
If there's a fudge
factor, great.

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:44.925
Grab it out of the source.

00:15:44.925 --> 00:15:46.390
It's a constant factor.

00:15:46.390 --> 00:15:48.460
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:15:48.460 --> 00:15:51.960
All right, so anyways I
really love this game.

00:15:51.960 --> 00:15:53.870
Honestly, it's an incredibly
well-designed game.

00:15:53.870 --> 00:15:54.750
It's really, really fun.

00:15:54.750 --> 00:15:56.460
The graphics are really
well done.

00:15:56.460 --> 00:16:00.160
It's very cute, and it
definitely is a game, looking

00:16:00.160 --> 00:16:02.592
around the Halloween season, I
think this is one that has

00:16:02.592 --> 00:16:04.530
legs that people are going
to want to play with.

