This game, I think, in terms of
a mobile game, this one's a

00:28:23.160 --> 00:28:23.495
little harder.

00:28:23.495 --> 00:28:28.740
It requires a large amount of
time investment to really get

00:28:28.740 --> 00:28:30.920
into and play this game.

00:28:30.920 --> 00:28:32.410
From a graphic prospective,
things are--

00:28:32.410 --> 00:28:33.343
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, that's cool.

00:28:33.343 --> 00:28:36.990
You know what this really
reminds me--

00:28:36.990 --> 00:28:39.400
how long has it been since
we've seen just a fun,

00:28:39.400 --> 00:28:42.660
top-down isometric?

00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:44.200
DAN GALPIN: I still
haven't seen one.

00:28:44.200 --> 00:28:46.130
But this is top-down
and isometric.

00:28:46.130 --> 00:28:47.180
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:28:47.180 --> 00:28:49.030
I guess that's sort of
mutually exclusive.

00:28:49.030 --> 00:28:50.610
But yeah, this is isometric.

00:28:50.610 --> 00:28:54.480
Well no, it reminds
me of "X-COM."

00:28:54.480 --> 00:28:55.970
But where's the shadows?

00:28:55.970 --> 00:28:56.450
Dude.

00:28:56.450 --> 00:28:57.460
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, I know.

00:28:57.460 --> 00:28:59.090
IAN NI-LEWIS: Shadows on these
characters aren't hard.

00:28:59.090 --> 00:28:59.670
All you need is a couple
of circles.

00:28:59.670 --> 00:29:00.810
DAN GALPIN: Not even
a fake shadow.

00:29:00.810 --> 00:29:03.710
There's even a little shadow
underneath that little marker.

00:29:03.710 --> 00:29:04.890
It's sort of odd.

00:29:04.890 --> 00:29:05.480
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah,
it's weird.

00:29:05.480 --> 00:29:07.390
DAN GALPIN: The graphics
are really blurry.

00:29:07.390 --> 00:29:09.010
I would love to see them
be a little higher

00:29:09.010 --> 00:29:10.210
res than they are.

00:29:10.210 --> 00:29:12.390
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's true.

00:29:12.390 --> 00:29:13.630
I didn't notice because--

00:29:13.630 --> 00:29:16.810
so here's a question
to our audience.

00:29:16.810 --> 00:29:20.460
We were just talking about
this the other day, is if

00:29:20.460 --> 00:29:22.460
you're going to run an automated
program to detect

00:29:22.460 --> 00:29:25.350
issues like this-- so what we're
talking about is over on

00:29:25.350 --> 00:29:28.860
the right side of the screen,
we've got these things that

00:29:28.860 --> 00:29:32.020
are almost behind Dan's head.

00:29:32.020 --> 00:29:33.890
So these are crisp.

00:29:33.890 --> 00:29:37.420
Whereas all of this, it's a
little hard to tell because

00:29:37.420 --> 00:29:40.750
it's so textured but
it is not crisp.

00:29:40.750 --> 00:29:42.090
I'd say the density is about--

00:29:42.090 --> 00:29:43.190
DAN GALPIN: Actually, it's
kind of nice because it

00:29:43.190 --> 00:29:46.155
creates depth of feel for
us in our shot here.

00:29:46.155 --> 00:29:47.130
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, yeah.

00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:47.685
Good point.

00:29:47.685 --> 00:29:48.840
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, exactly.

00:29:48.840 --> 00:29:49.860
It looks like it's
way behind us.

00:29:49.860 --> 00:29:52.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: Except we like
we're sort of positioned in a

00:29:52.440 --> 00:29:56.000
weird netherspace over
an isometric field.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:58.480
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, well,
I think that's OK.

00:29:58.480 --> 00:30:00.470
IAN NI-LEWIS: Anyway, the point
is, what would you do to

00:30:00.470 --> 00:30:01.730
detect this?

00:30:01.730 --> 00:30:05.600
Because to put it in layman's
terms, I think we're trying to

00:30:05.600 --> 00:30:08.620
detect places where--

00:30:08.620 --> 00:30:12.050
there's crisp, but then
most of it's blurry.

00:30:12.050 --> 00:30:15.590
But the problem is, if you're
just measuring frequency or

00:30:15.590 --> 00:30:17.690
whatever, some things
are going to be a

00:30:17.690 --> 00:30:19.470
low-frequency signal.

00:30:19.470 --> 00:30:23.770
And especially things like this
gameplay, the only places

00:30:23.770 --> 00:30:26.870
that you notice it, the only
places where it has to be

00:30:26.870 --> 00:30:29.710
crisp, are the places that you
would expect it to be crisp.

00:30:29.710 --> 00:30:30.590
And maybe that's it.

00:30:30.590 --> 00:30:32.810
Maybe what we need to do is
shrink it down, find the

00:30:32.810 --> 00:30:35.660
silhouette edges, and then see
how many of the silhouette

00:30:35.660 --> 00:30:37.880
edges are actually blurry
at higher resolutions.

00:30:37.880 --> 00:30:38.680
DAN GALPIN: Well, exactly.

00:30:38.680 --> 00:30:40.430
It would also be an interesting
example to do just

00:30:40.430 --> 00:30:42.430
that-- to actually change
the size of the display.

00:30:42.430 --> 00:30:47.000
Look at this game at different
display sizes and compare how

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:48.020
blurry it gets.

00:30:48.020 --> 00:30:51.870
And then we could actually see
where it had the highest

00:30:51.870 --> 00:30:53.120
amount of information.

00:30:55.480 --> 00:30:56.280
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah,
that's true.

00:30:56.280 --> 00:30:58.960
If we just characterize the
information theoretically, if

00:30:58.960 --> 00:31:02.970
the information doesn't go up
when the screen size does,

00:31:02.970 --> 00:31:03.940
then that's a problem, right?

00:31:03.940 --> 00:31:05.280
DAN GALPIN: Exactly.

00:31:05.280 --> 00:31:07.030
We'd even take each image
and apply a scale

00:31:07.030 --> 00:31:07.890
factor, scale it down--

00:31:07.890 --> 00:31:08.590
IAN NI-LEWIS: No,
you're right.

00:31:08.590 --> 00:31:09.550
You're absolutely right.

00:31:09.550 --> 00:31:11.570
Because that's the truth.

00:31:11.570 --> 00:31:13.230
It doesn't have anything
to do with frequency.

00:31:13.230 --> 00:31:16.300
It has to do with information.

00:31:16.300 --> 00:31:20.580
Because if you're making a
bilinear prediction at each

00:31:20.580 --> 00:31:24.770
pixel, and the prediction is
always right, then there's no

00:31:24.770 --> 00:31:27.460
information beyond what
the quarter of the

00:31:27.460 --> 00:31:28.566
size would have been.

00:31:28.566 --> 00:31:29.670
DAN GALPIN: Exactly.

00:31:29.670 --> 00:31:30.430
IAN NI-LEWIS: Genius.

00:31:30.430 --> 00:31:31.310
DAN GALPIN: Well--

00:31:31.310 --> 00:31:33.720
thank you-- we're solving all
of our problems here on the

00:31:33.720 --> 00:31:35.060
Friday Review.

00:31:35.060 --> 00:31:37.920
But yeah, so this game is really
blurry on tablets.

00:31:37.920 --> 00:31:38.580
It's OK on phones.

00:31:38.580 --> 00:31:41.290
Honestly, on a Galaxy Nexus,
you can see this too.

00:31:41.290 --> 00:31:42.300
IAN NI-LEWIS: All right,
well, I'm really bored.

