DAN GALPIN: Well,
I love anonymous

00:38:21.270 --> 00:38:22.210
matchmaking, actually.

00:38:22.210 --> 00:38:24.730
I think that mobile really
lends to it.

00:38:24.730 --> 00:38:25.920
I've got five minutes here.

00:38:25.920 --> 00:38:28.940
I have no time to
grab friends.

00:38:28.940 --> 00:38:31.670
And that happened all the
time, even in "World of

00:38:31.670 --> 00:38:34.240
Warcraft." You'd run into a
bunch of people-- hey, we're

00:38:34.240 --> 00:38:36.060
all about to do this
same mission.

00:38:36.060 --> 00:38:37.090
Awesome, can I join you?

00:38:37.090 --> 00:38:38.310
Yes, let's go to kill the

00:38:38.310 --> 00:38:39.830
blah-blah and get the blah-blah.

00:38:39.830 --> 00:38:42.940
And so that kind of stuff, I
think, lends itself very, very

00:38:42.940 --> 00:38:44.140
well to mobile.

00:38:44.140 --> 00:38:46.730
An example would be "Dungeon
Hunter 3," actually, has a

00:38:46.730 --> 00:38:49.280
mode where you say, hey,
I've got a room.

00:38:49.280 --> 00:38:50.190
Let's find other people.

00:38:50.190 --> 00:38:51.340
Let's go attack this.

00:38:51.340 --> 00:38:53.670
That works really well, and you
don't have to find a whole

00:38:53.670 --> 00:38:55.230
bunch of friends to do it.

00:38:55.230 --> 00:38:56.720
And you can actually chat.

00:38:56.720 --> 00:39:00.340
But it's such a pain to chat on
mobile that it leaves the

00:39:00.340 --> 00:39:02.200
conversation, actually,
relatively short.

00:39:02.200 --> 00:39:02.640
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, that's
really tough.

00:39:02.640 --> 00:39:04.990
I don't think that I really got
into multi-player gaming

00:39:04.990 --> 00:39:09.420
until voice chat became
ubiquitous.

00:39:09.420 --> 00:39:14.030
Now, theoretically, there
wouldn't be anything stopping

00:39:14.030 --> 00:39:18.630
somebody from releasing a chat
client that could run in the

00:39:18.630 --> 00:39:21.430
background and do the stuff.

00:39:21.430 --> 00:39:27.270
Again, I'm always astounded by
how much amazing computing

00:39:27.270 --> 00:39:29.240
power we can carry in our
pocket, but we're still

00:39:29.240 --> 00:39:30.600
carrying it in our pocket
and powering it

00:39:30.600 --> 00:39:32.020
by tiny little batteries.

00:39:32.020 --> 00:39:34.190
It's nothing compared to
something that you

00:39:34.190 --> 00:39:34.940
plug into the wall.

00:39:34.940 --> 00:39:36.130
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, it's true.

00:39:36.130 --> 00:39:39.880
And I think that we're
going to get there.

00:39:39.880 --> 00:39:43.550
But currently, in terms of
multi-player, I think that

00:39:43.550 --> 00:39:47.240
there are certainly fantastic
success stories in mobile.

00:39:47.240 --> 00:39:50.130
But most of them have been
asynchronous multi-player.

00:39:50.130 --> 00:39:52.280
Or the other thing that works
really, really well that I

00:39:52.280 --> 00:39:56.030
like to see are challenges where
you actually can play

00:39:56.030 --> 00:39:58.230
against the ghost of someone.

00:39:58.230 --> 00:40:00.750
Your friend can be like, nyah,
nyah, I just got this high

00:40:00.750 --> 00:40:02.510
score and et cetera,
et cetera.

00:40:02.510 --> 00:40:05.220
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right, because
that's really when I'm gaming

00:40:05.220 --> 00:40:07.020
on my phone is because
I've got a little

00:40:07.020 --> 00:40:08.120
bit of time to grab.

00:40:08.120 --> 00:40:11.760
And I need the experience that
is going to reward that as

00:40:11.760 --> 00:40:14.540
opposed to having to
call up my friend.

00:40:14.540 --> 00:40:17.350
And of course, it'll say my
friend is online, but of

00:40:17.350 --> 00:40:19.240
course he's online because
he's got his

00:40:19.240 --> 00:40:20.060
phone in his pocket.

00:40:20.060 --> 00:40:21.570
Everybody always does, right?

00:40:21.570 --> 00:40:22.300
DAN GALPIN: Exactly.

00:40:22.300 --> 00:40:23.490
IAN NI-LEWIS: So it's tough.

00:40:23.490 --> 00:40:25.880
I mean, there's definitely
challenges that we didn't face

00:40:25.880 --> 00:40:29.190
when we were doing the
desktop stuff.

00:40:29.190 --> 00:40:30.580
DAN GALPIN: Yeah,
or on the Xbox.

00:40:30.580 --> 00:40:33.600
You're on the Xbox, most likely,
you're either watching

00:40:33.600 --> 00:40:37.850
videos-- in which case, man,
don't even try to message me--

00:40:37.850 --> 00:40:40.190
or you're playing games, in
which case-- well, actually,

00:40:40.190 --> 00:40:42.360
don't try to message me most
of the time either.

00:40:42.360 --> 00:40:42.740
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, yeah.

00:40:42.740 --> 00:40:44.140
Yeah, that's pissing me off.

00:40:44.140 --> 00:40:45.505
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:40:45.505 --> 00:40:48.710
Can't you see, man?

00:40:48.710 --> 00:40:51.040
But at least you're actively at
a console where you usually

00:40:51.040 --> 00:40:54.300
have a fast internet connection
and you're in the

00:40:54.300 --> 00:40:56.820
mood to potentially interact
with humans,

00:40:56.820 --> 00:40:58.580
although not always.

00:40:58.580 --> 00:41:01.510
LOUIS: Any concerns about
multi-player bandwidth?

00:41:01.510 --> 00:41:02.320
IAN NI-LEWIS: Of course.

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:06.710
Although I would say that the
bandwidth issue is much less

00:41:06.710 --> 00:41:09.110
of a concern than latency.

00:41:09.110 --> 00:41:10.600
You can always fix bandwidth.

00:41:10.600 --> 00:41:12.830
It's very difficult
to fix latency.

00:41:12.830 --> 00:41:14.860
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, I think we're
finally getting into

00:41:14.860 --> 00:41:15.510
some networks.

00:41:15.510 --> 00:41:18.690
Like, LTE has some actually
great latency numbers on a

00:41:18.690 --> 00:41:20.660
non-congested network.

00:41:20.660 --> 00:41:22.660
And so we're finally getting to
the point where some of the

00:41:22.660 --> 00:41:24.800
things that were at one point
either limited to either LAN

00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:25.800
connections--

00:41:25.800 --> 00:41:29.010
it's kind of funny.

00:41:29.010 --> 00:41:32.990
My friends who were serious
about gaming would be like,

00:41:32.990 --> 00:41:35.370
all right, I can't have a cable
modem because there's

00:41:35.370 --> 00:41:36.280
too much latency.

00:41:36.280 --> 00:41:38.870
I can't be on Wi-Fi because that
adds too much latency to

00:41:38.870 --> 00:41:42.090
the DSL line, which is the
only thing it provides

00:41:42.090 --> 00:41:42.430
[? alone ?]

00:41:42.430 --> 00:41:45.860
of latency so that I have a
chance of not getting fragged.

00:41:45.860 --> 00:41:50.650
And we're not anywhere near that
in terms of mobile yet.

00:41:50.650 --> 00:41:53.670
But there are certain kinds of
twitch experiences that are

00:41:53.670 --> 00:41:59.320
starting to work on an actual
cellular network.

00:41:59.320 --> 00:42:00.700
And I think that's exciting.

00:42:00.700 --> 00:42:01.980
LTE is really enabling
all that.

00:42:01.980 --> 00:42:03.830
So I think we'll see
more and more.

00:42:03.830 --> 00:42:04.740
But it still is tricky.

00:42:04.740 --> 00:42:06.580
And one of the things is, when
you're doing matchmaking, you

00:42:06.580 --> 00:42:08.540
want to find out, how
good are my pings?

00:42:08.540 --> 00:42:10.150
Can I get a quality
of service?

00:42:10.150 --> 00:42:12.620
If the quality of service
falls below a certain

00:42:12.620 --> 00:42:14.320
threshold, what does that mean
in terms of the game?

00:42:14.320 --> 00:42:15.370
It does add additional
design challenges.

00:42:15.370 --> 00:42:18.445
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, really, I
think, the biggest problem is

00:42:18.445 --> 00:42:22.720
that your ping time is extremely
unpredictable when

00:42:22.720 --> 00:42:24.740
you're own mobile.

00:42:24.740 --> 00:42:27.385
Even if you're stationary, it
can be very unpredictable

00:42:27.385 --> 00:42:30.255
because it's so susceptible
to ARP interference.

00:42:30.255 --> 00:42:33.000
DAN GALPIN: Our Wi-Fi
is actually a

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:33.880
perfect test ground.

00:42:33.880 --> 00:42:36.410
If something works on our Wi-Fi
here, it probably will

00:42:36.410 --> 00:42:37.980
work on a mobile network

00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:40.900
IAN NI-LEWIS: That might
actually be true, yeah.

00:42:40.900 --> 00:42:45.250
But I mean, if you've got a
femtocell or a Wi-Fi network,

00:42:45.250 --> 00:42:48.350
I think that there's all sorts
of things you can do.

00:42:48.350 --> 00:42:51.510
The nice thing is that the
same games that lend

00:42:51.510 --> 00:42:55.980
themselves particularly well
to a touch-screen only

00:42:55.980 --> 00:42:59.160
interface are the same games
that very frequently don't

00:42:59.160 --> 00:43:02.060
require incredibly
good latency.

00:43:04.900 --> 00:43:08.640
So I'm sure there are people
who really honestly enjoy

00:43:08.640 --> 00:43:16.710
playing FPSs on mobile, I'm not
one of them just because I

00:43:16.710 --> 00:43:20.560
feel like I have so many better
ways to play FPSs.

00:43:20.560 --> 00:43:24.730
And I don't have a better way
to play, let's say, "Tower

00:43:24.730 --> 00:43:28.005
Defense" or, like I said, RTS.

00:43:28.005 --> 00:43:31.420
And the nice thing about those
games is that while they're

00:43:31.420 --> 00:43:35.690
not fully deterministic, it's
really, really easy to do

00:43:35.690 --> 00:43:37.270
latency hiding in those
situations.

00:43:37.270 --> 00:43:40.350
Now, one of my favorite
multi-player games, as you all

00:43:40.350 --> 00:43:43.140
know, is the "Big Win"
series by Hot Head.

00:43:43.140 --> 00:43:48.480
And they hide latency
beautifully just by

00:43:48.480 --> 00:43:51.290
pre-computing everything.

00:43:51.290 --> 00:43:53.270
But here's the dirty
little secret--

00:43:53.270 --> 00:43:55.680
you're like, oh, well, yeah,
of course it's all

00:43:55.680 --> 00:43:56.230
predetermined.

00:43:56.230 --> 00:44:00.920
But the truth is that most
sports games can do very

00:44:00.920 --> 00:44:01.990
similar things.

00:44:01.990 --> 00:44:07.690
For instance, "NFL Fever" and
"NHL Rivals" from Microsoft

00:44:07.690 --> 00:44:15.060
sports, we would basically start
an animation sooner on

00:44:15.060 --> 00:44:21.260
the originating client and hold
it out for more frames.

00:44:21.260 --> 00:44:24.480
And this is the same thing
as the old "Warcraft" and

00:44:24.480 --> 00:44:30.980
"StarCraft." if you click on a
peon, and he says, OK, I'm

00:44:30.980 --> 00:44:32.510
going to do my thing.

00:44:32.510 --> 00:44:36.570
And he is acting lazy, well,
that's not laziness on your

00:44:36.570 --> 00:44:37.140
peon's part.

00:44:37.140 --> 00:44:38.440
That's latency compensation.

00:44:38.440 --> 00:44:42.520
Because if you can hold off on
actually doing the thing for 5

00:44:42.520 --> 00:44:47.590
or 10 frames, which isn't very
long, then you can completely

00:44:47.590 --> 00:44:49.840
get rid of ping time problems.

00:44:49.840 --> 00:44:50.930
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:44:50.930 --> 00:44:53.880
And listen, I've played
a lot of FPS games

00:44:53.880 --> 00:44:55.315
a lot now on mobile.

00:44:55.315 --> 00:44:58.380
"Shadowgun" was a great
experience.

00:44:58.380 --> 00:44:58.842
IAN NI-LEWIS: It always
flabbergasts me

00:44:58.842 --> 00:44:59.690
that you can do that.

00:44:59.690 --> 00:45:01.230
DAN GALPIN: Except for the one
level where you have to run

00:45:01.230 --> 00:45:03.900
backwards, which made me
want to shoot someone.

00:45:03.900 --> 00:45:05.460
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, was
that when the drill

00:45:05.460 --> 00:45:06.460
came through the wall?

00:45:06.460 --> 00:45:07.080
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, the
drill's coming.

00:45:07.080 --> 00:45:07.800
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, that
was terrible.

00:45:07.800 --> 00:45:08.500
DAN GALPIN: Just awful.

00:45:08.500 --> 00:45:10.710
IAN NI-LEWIS: That was the meat
circus of "Shadowgun."

00:45:10.710 --> 00:45:11.800
DAN GALPIN: It actually was.

00:45:11.800 --> 00:45:13.820
And you just got ground
up over and over.

00:45:13.820 --> 00:45:15.135
And I made it through.

00:45:15.135 --> 00:45:17.880
I actually beat that
level twice.

00:45:17.880 --> 00:45:18.650
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's right.

00:45:18.650 --> 00:45:21.140
You had to beat that level
because we had to get past it

00:45:21.140 --> 00:45:22.630
to show it in Barcelona,
right?

00:45:22.630 --> 00:45:24.590
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, in Mobile
World Congress.

00:45:24.590 --> 00:45:26.380
I was like, I'm gonna
pass this level.

00:45:26.380 --> 00:45:27.530
IAN NI-LEWIS: That
was hilarious.

00:45:27.530 --> 00:45:31.130
DAN GALPIN: But yeah, I played
"Shadowgun," I played "Dead

00:45:31.130 --> 00:45:32.900
Trigger," actually I played
through "Batman--

00:45:32.900 --> 00:45:40.410
The Dark Night." I played
through a lot of "Spider-Man."

00:45:40.410 --> 00:45:41.760
I love "Mass Effect:
Infiltrator."

00:45:41.760 --> 00:45:42.885
Did I say that already?

00:45:42.885 --> 00:45:43.990
IAN NI-LEWIS: Of
course you did.

00:45:43.990 --> 00:45:45.560
DAN GALPIN: I played through a
lot of that. "Dead Trigger," I

00:45:45.560 --> 00:45:46.470
did a lot of.

00:45:46.470 --> 00:45:48.050
There's been a lot
of really, really

00:45:48.050 --> 00:45:52.240
great experiences there.

00:45:52.240 --> 00:45:54.090
And it's interesting because
there's two different models.

00:45:54.090 --> 00:45:56.470
There's ones like "Mass Effect"
which really tries to

00:45:56.470 --> 00:46:00.760
use swiping and to create a
totally different interface--

00:46:00.760 --> 00:46:05.040
and sometimes it just
drives me crazy--

00:46:05.040 --> 00:46:08.290
and then there are the things
like "Shadowgun," which are

00:46:08.290 --> 00:46:10.710
basically doing joystick
simulations.

00:46:10.710 --> 00:46:12.570
And it was funny because I
actually don't know what I

00:46:12.570 --> 00:46:15.895
like more because I totally
appreciate the crazy stuff

00:46:15.895 --> 00:46:17.300
"Mass Effect: Infiltrator"
does.

00:46:17.300 --> 00:46:20.330
But the problem is when you're
actually playing on a tablet,

00:46:20.330 --> 00:46:21.870
you are just reaching
all over the place.

00:46:21.870 --> 00:46:24.440
You're going up to the corner
and dragging stuff and doing

00:46:24.440 --> 00:46:26.130
gestures here and there.

00:46:26.130 --> 00:46:28.485
And it does get to be
a little bit crazy.

00:46:28.485 --> 00:46:31.570
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, I feel like
that's a common problem,

00:46:31.570 --> 00:46:34.380
is that people will design a
great touch interface, but

00:46:34.380 --> 00:46:37.060
they'll design it around a
particular form factor.

00:46:37.060 --> 00:46:41.800
And that's not the world
we live in anymore.

00:46:41.800 --> 00:46:44.940
And Android has lots
of form factors.

00:46:44.940 --> 00:46:46.300
Everybody has at least two.

00:46:46.300 --> 00:46:48.280
DAN GALPIN: Well, my favorite is
"N.O.V.A. 3." So "N.O.V.A.

00:46:48.280 --> 00:46:51.680
3" actually has a mode, you can
actually go and drag the

00:46:51.680 --> 00:46:53.540
different controls around.

00:46:53.540 --> 00:46:58.530
Except you can't actually drag
the one that does reload, with

00:46:58.530 --> 00:46:59.760
is stuck at the top
of the screen.

00:46:59.760 --> 00:47:01.640
So you can have everything
else right within thumb's

00:47:01.640 --> 00:47:03.300
reach, and then you're
going, reload.

00:47:03.300 --> 00:47:04.660
All right, back, back, back.

00:47:04.660 --> 00:47:06.300
Reload.

00:47:06.300 --> 00:47:11.840
So again, kudos, I love the
concept of having customizable

00:47:11.840 --> 00:47:14.340
controls, but they kind of all
have to be customizable at

00:47:14.340 --> 00:47:16.780
that point.

00:47:16.780 --> 00:47:20.200
And again, "N.O.V.A. 3" is great
for that kind of game.

00:47:20.200 --> 00:47:23.890
But definitely, we're at an
era where the hardware can

00:47:23.890 --> 00:47:25.760
actually do some really
nice FPSs.

00:47:25.760 --> 00:47:28.990
We're seeing stuff that rivals,
in many ways, actually

00:47:28.990 --> 00:47:31.370
is better quality than what we
saw on the PS2 and on the

00:47:31.370 --> 00:47:32.480
original Xbox.

00:47:32.480 --> 00:47:34.410
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, you can
definitely get past the Xbox 1

00:47:34.410 --> 00:47:36.030
and PS2 phase.

00:47:36.030 --> 00:47:39.190
For me, I didn't actually get
into FPSs until the Xbox 360,

00:47:39.190 --> 00:47:40.970
and I'll tell you why.

00:47:40.970 --> 00:47:44.070
Part of it was that was
the first console--

00:47:44.070 --> 00:47:47.560
and you remember, that came
out before the PS3.

00:47:47.560 --> 00:47:53.970
So it was the first console
that had a unified shader.

00:47:53.970 --> 00:47:57.100
And it was also the first
console that had any real

00:47:57.100 --> 00:48:00.470
memory, so it drove really
high texel density.

00:48:00.470 --> 00:48:04.870
And I just found that the blurry
stuff is really hard to

00:48:04.870 --> 00:48:05.990
go back to.

00:48:05.990 --> 00:48:10.260
DAN GALPIN: And I will say, I
played a crap-load of "Halo"

00:48:10.260 --> 00:48:12.870
and "Halo 2" on the
original Xbox.

00:48:12.870 --> 00:48:15.120
And we used to get together for
LAN parties and we used to

00:48:15.120 --> 00:48:15.995
have Frag-fest.

00:48:15.995 --> 00:48:17.760
And that was really fun.

00:48:17.760 --> 00:48:21.520
In fact, I love just the fact
that we had to put everyone

00:48:21.520 --> 00:48:23.790
together in the same room and we
had everyone walking around

00:48:23.790 --> 00:48:28.160
carrying these gi-normous
Xboxes and monitors.

00:48:28.160 --> 00:48:29.720
Super-dorky but kind
of awesome.

