Korean?

00:49:06.790 --> 00:49:07.130
Bye.

00:49:07.130 --> 00:49:07.420
DAN GALPIN: I know.

00:49:07.420 --> 00:49:09.750
Yeah, exactly.

00:49:09.750 --> 00:49:10.960
No, I don't think she's
actually in Korea now.

00:49:10.960 --> 00:49:14.350
I think she had another meeting
today, actually.

00:49:14.350 --> 00:49:15.200
IAN NI-LEWIS: Of
course she did.

00:49:15.200 --> 00:49:15.760
DAN GALPIN: Of course she did.

00:49:15.760 --> 00:49:16.500
IAN NI-LEWIS: Of
course she did.

00:49:16.500 --> 00:49:17.490
Anything else on there, Louis?

00:49:17.490 --> 00:49:19.230
LOUIS: There's lots of questions
around nomination of

00:49:19.230 --> 00:49:22.220
games, either to get reviewed
here, but also featuring.

00:49:22.220 --> 00:49:26.640
The developer of "Greedy Monkey"
is watching, one of

00:49:26.640 --> 00:49:27.210
those which is on display.

00:49:27.210 --> 00:49:29.049
And of course, they want to
know, how do they get to the

00:49:29.049 --> 00:49:31.190
next step and get behind the
featuring committee?

00:49:31.190 --> 00:49:33.620
DAN GALPIN: Well, I mean,
the truth is, on

00:49:33.620 --> 00:49:35.040
a tablet like this--

00:49:35.040 --> 00:49:37.730
I haven't had extensive
experience on a phone-- but in

00:49:37.730 --> 00:49:39.850
terms of something like "Greedy
Monkey," you have to

00:49:39.850 --> 00:49:41.420
look at the quality of the stuff
that's getting featured

00:49:41.420 --> 00:49:44.560
now in terms of just the
graphical integrity that we're

00:49:44.560 --> 00:49:45.380
talking about.

00:49:45.380 --> 00:49:46.510
The bar is pretty high.

00:49:46.510 --> 00:49:48.350
And the reason is because
they're taking this game and

00:49:48.350 --> 00:49:52.880
they're putting it in front of
millions and millions of

00:49:52.880 --> 00:49:53.450
Android users.

00:49:53.450 --> 00:49:56.180
We're talking about over a
million activations a day of

00:49:56.180 --> 00:49:58.480
just new devices, not to mention
all the ones that are

00:49:58.480 --> 00:49:59.170
sitting out there.

00:49:59.170 --> 00:50:03.650
And so the bar has
gotten higher.

00:50:03.650 --> 00:50:05.040
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, there's
a few things there.

00:50:05.040 --> 00:50:09.710
I mean, in terms of the
bar, the minimum bar--

00:50:09.710 --> 00:50:12.835
we published it just a few
days ago on developer--

00:50:12.835 --> 00:50:13.350
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, we have an
app quality checklist.

00:50:13.350 --> 00:50:18.030
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, the app
quality checklist, essentially

00:50:18.030 --> 00:50:20.800
that's derived from the
guidelines that Dan and I

00:50:20.800 --> 00:50:23.410
helped write for game
featuring quality.

00:50:23.410 --> 00:50:25.840
DAN GALPIN: A shout out
to our QA team who

00:50:25.840 --> 00:50:26.610
did an amazing job.

00:50:26.610 --> 00:50:29.560
IAN NI-LEWIS: Ian Armstrong
actually put them into words.

00:50:29.560 --> 00:50:32.210
He is so much more literate
than us when it

00:50:32.210 --> 00:50:33.560
comes to test plans.

00:50:33.560 --> 00:50:35.190
DAN GALPIN: And it was
interesting because what's

00:50:35.190 --> 00:50:38.140
great about the quality
guidelines is that you can

00:50:38.140 --> 00:50:39.800
actually use it as
a test plan.

00:50:39.800 --> 00:50:42.010
So it actually says, here are
the things that we're trying

00:50:42.010 --> 00:50:42.810
to test for.

00:50:42.810 --> 00:50:45.070
And then it actually says, and
here are a bunch of tests you

00:50:45.070 --> 00:50:48.040
may use to actually try to
test for those things.

00:50:48.040 --> 00:50:50.660
So first of all, everyone should
look at app quality and

00:50:50.660 --> 00:50:54.210
tablet app quality, especially
for games, and try to make

00:50:54.210 --> 00:50:56.480
sure that it gets there.

00:50:56.480 --> 00:50:59.720
And so part of it, they're going
to look at graphics in

00:50:59.720 --> 00:51:03.870
terms of style, in terms
of pixel density.

00:51:03.870 --> 00:51:06.690
And "Greedy Monkey," it needs to
be taken to the next level

00:51:06.690 --> 00:51:07.220
in terms of polish.

00:51:07.220 --> 00:51:08.970
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, let's
see what's featured now.

00:51:08.970 --> 00:51:11.755
The other thing that I think is
really important for people

00:51:11.755 --> 00:51:19.930
to understand is that the
featured apps have to be at

00:51:19.930 --> 00:51:23.790
least four stars and
lots of downloads.

00:51:23.790 --> 00:51:25.540
DAN GALPIN: Almost always.

00:51:25.540 --> 00:51:27.700
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, every now
and then, we'll go looking for

00:51:27.700 --> 00:51:28.750
diamonds in the rough,
for sure.

00:51:28.750 --> 00:51:30.090
DAN GALPIN: Well, if
there's velocity.

00:51:30.090 --> 00:51:32.480
So sometimes what happens is
some guy publishes a game

00:51:32.480 --> 00:51:33.580
that's awesome.

00:51:33.580 --> 00:51:37.160
Except that they didn't test it
on anything but one device.

00:51:37.160 --> 00:51:38.920
And then there's like,
everyone starts

00:51:38.920 --> 00:51:39.880
giving it one star.

00:51:39.880 --> 00:51:42.760
IAN NI-LEWIS: So occasionally
we'll see a game that has what

00:51:42.760 --> 00:51:46.670
we call a U-shaped distribution
for reviews.

00:51:46.670 --> 00:51:49.100
So it'll be like all
fives and all ones

00:51:49.100 --> 00:51:50.250
and nothing in between.

00:51:50.250 --> 00:51:53.140
And that's a really good sign
that we should feature this

00:51:53.140 --> 00:51:56.960
game as soon as they fix
or blacklist devices.

00:51:56.960 --> 00:51:58.630
And that's very typical.

00:51:58.630 --> 00:52:00.440
But let's take a look--

00:52:00.440 --> 00:52:01.900
DAN GALPIN: I haven't played
"Death Dome." That looks

00:52:01.900 --> 00:52:02.590
pretty cool.

00:52:02.590 --> 00:52:06.450
IAN NI-LEWIS: This does
look pretty cool.

00:52:06.450 --> 00:52:07.800
DAN GALPIN: I haven't played
it yet, but I want

00:52:07.800 --> 00:52:08.770
to give it one star.

00:52:08.770 --> 00:52:10.320
Wait, what is that review?

00:52:10.320 --> 00:52:12.110
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, that's
an awesome review.

00:52:12.110 --> 00:52:14.030
I totally want--

00:52:14.030 --> 00:52:14.550
DAN GALPIN: Why?

00:52:14.550 --> 00:52:17.260
Because it won't even open and
finish downloading the data.

00:52:17.260 --> 00:52:18.550
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, yeah.

00:52:18.550 --> 00:52:20.230
That's a good--

00:52:20.230 --> 00:52:23.550
and there's not that many one
star reviews on this site.

00:52:23.550 --> 00:52:24.160
DAN GALPIN: That's
unusual, yeah.

00:52:24.160 --> 00:52:25.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: Most people
seem to be doing well.

00:52:25.440 --> 00:52:33.530
But if you look at these things,
it used to be that we

00:52:33.530 --> 00:52:36.040
were desperate for games.

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:38.480
I'm talking about a while ago.

00:52:38.480 --> 00:52:41.810
DAN GALPIN: Three years ago,
if the game played and it

00:52:41.810 --> 00:52:42.770
looked OK--

00:52:42.770 --> 00:52:44.750
but now, the bar is so high.

00:52:44.750 --> 00:52:47.210
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, like,
"Pirates of the Caribbean,"

00:52:47.210 --> 00:52:48.330
that's a Disney game.

00:52:48.330 --> 00:52:50.180
You've got Gameloft, Com2uS.

00:52:50.180 --> 00:52:52.910
DAN GALPIN: "NFL Pro." "Rayman
Jungle Run" is awesome.

00:52:52.910 --> 00:52:53.925
"Bard's Tale" is epic.

00:52:53.925 --> 00:52:55.470
IAN NI-LEWIS: The truth is
that the top five or six

00:52:55.470 --> 00:52:57.740
developers put out more
games than we

00:52:57.740 --> 00:52:59.600
could possibly feature.

00:52:59.600 --> 00:53:01.615
DAN GALPIN: Again, look at all
the independents here, though.

00:53:01.615 --> 00:53:02.370
It's awesome.

00:53:02.370 --> 00:53:02.830
IAN NI-LEWIS: But we do.

00:53:02.830 --> 00:53:03.370
Yeah, exactly.

00:53:03.370 --> 00:53:05.010
So that's the thing.

00:53:05.010 --> 00:53:08.690
I guess what I'm trying to say
is, if all we wanted to do was

00:53:08.690 --> 00:53:16.240
feature great quality games,
there are a huge number that

00:53:16.240 --> 00:53:20.660
are made by really, really
well-funded people.

00:53:20.660 --> 00:53:23.950
We don't just want to feature
well-funded games or games by

00:53:23.950 --> 00:53:26.040
the top five developers.

00:53:26.040 --> 00:53:30.570
We really, really want to
feature some other things.

00:53:30.570 --> 00:53:35.190
But usually what it takes is a
very strong recommendation.

00:53:35.190 --> 00:53:39.040
Sometimes it will be people that
just made it really big

00:53:39.040 --> 00:53:39.950
on other platforms.

00:53:39.950 --> 00:53:43.400
Like for instance, "Triple
Town" was very big on the

00:53:43.400 --> 00:53:44.970
original Kindle.

00:53:44.970 --> 00:53:46.960
DAN GALPIN: Well, "Triple
Town" was just an

00:53:46.960 --> 00:53:47.710
incredibly fun game.

00:53:47.710 --> 00:53:48.870
IAN NI-LEWIS: Plus we're
buddies with that guy.

00:53:48.870 --> 00:53:49.610
He's a really good guy.

00:53:49.610 --> 00:53:53.740
He used to run Xbox
live arcades.

00:53:53.740 --> 00:53:57.140
DAN GALPIN: But I think with
"Triple Town," it was one of

00:53:57.140 --> 00:53:58.610
those that actually
got submitted.

00:53:58.610 --> 00:54:00.820
So "Triple Town" went through
a process-- it got submitted

00:54:00.820 --> 00:54:02.370
to a whole bunch of Googlers
who were just

00:54:02.370 --> 00:54:03.905
randomly looking at games.

00:54:03.905 --> 00:54:07.900
And all of them lost so
much productivity.

00:54:07.900 --> 00:54:12.000
Literally, these people came
back to us and said, you can't

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:16.320
recommend this kind of game to
us because we just are missing

00:54:16.320 --> 00:54:18.560
all of our objectives and key
results for the quarter

00:54:18.560 --> 00:54:20.280
because of "Triple Town."

00:54:20.280 --> 00:54:22.660
IAN NI-LEWIS: But here's really
what it comes down to--

00:54:22.660 --> 00:54:24.850
a lot of people say, well,
how do I get noticed?

00:54:24.850 --> 00:54:29.210
And we did for a while
run this show as a

00:54:29.210 --> 00:54:30.350
crowd-sourcing thing.

00:54:30.350 --> 00:54:31.760
We've kind of stopped
doing that.

00:54:31.760 --> 00:54:34.680
We've kind of stopped thinking
of this as being a conduit

00:54:34.680 --> 00:54:37.010
into featuring because
we just weren't

00:54:37.010 --> 00:54:39.160
seeing good enough results.

00:54:39.160 --> 00:54:44.740
It turns out that there's a lot
of really intriguing indie

00:54:44.740 --> 00:54:48.190
stuff by people who are
super-low budget.

00:54:48.190 --> 00:54:53.480
But for the most part, the
really, really good stuff

00:54:53.480 --> 00:54:54.640
floats to the top.

00:54:54.640 --> 00:54:58.560
So for instance, we look at
the Android gamer sites.

00:54:58.560 --> 00:55:01.890
We look at the mobile
gamer sites.

00:55:01.890 --> 00:55:05.510
We talk to developers and say,
what are you playing?

00:55:05.510 --> 00:55:09.690
So I don't think we're the
ones that are going to

00:55:09.690 --> 00:55:11.140
discover you is really what
it comes down to.

00:55:11.140 --> 00:55:13.040
DAN GALPIN: There have been a
couple of games that have come

00:55:13.040 --> 00:55:15.350
through here that have
become featured.

00:55:15.350 --> 00:55:17.480
And a couple of ones
where they were--

00:55:17.480 --> 00:55:18.390
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:55:18.390 --> 00:55:20.640
Like "Gunman Clive,"
for instance, we

00:55:20.640 --> 00:55:21.740
all loved that game.

00:55:21.740 --> 00:55:22.850
We hadn't seen it before.

00:55:22.850 --> 00:55:23.640
Absolutely.

00:55:23.640 --> 00:55:25.750
And I think that that
will still happen.

00:55:25.750 --> 00:55:26.950
But you have to understand--

00:55:26.950 --> 00:55:27.520
DAN GALPIN: "Word Hero"
was another one.

00:55:27.520 --> 00:55:28.660
IAN NI-LEWIS: --that the
bar is really high.

00:55:28.660 --> 00:55:30.300
DAN GALPIN: "Word Hero" here
came through here, and we're

00:55:30.300 --> 00:55:32.550
like, with some polish,
this game has all

00:55:32.550 --> 00:55:33.320
of the right bones.

00:55:33.320 --> 00:55:34.320
It's going to be a great game.

00:55:34.320 --> 00:55:38.680
And I've never seen a developer
work so hard to

00:55:38.680 --> 00:55:41.244
polish their game and get it
ready for tablets and get it

00:55:41.244 --> 00:55:43.140
ready for multiple devices
and get a much

00:55:43.140 --> 00:55:44.110
better feature graphic.

00:55:44.110 --> 00:55:48.680
And he did great stuff to
make sure that it was

00:55:48.680 --> 00:55:49.520
going to pass our--

00:55:49.520 --> 00:55:50.990
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's another
thing, by the way.

00:55:50.990 --> 00:55:52.260
Look at these feature
graphics.

00:55:52.260 --> 00:55:53.100
They're lush.

00:55:53.100 --> 00:55:53.500
They're beautiful.

00:55:53.500 --> 00:55:54.380
DAN GALPIN: I mean,
"Clouds &amp; Sheep."

00:55:54.380 --> 00:55:55.155
IAN NI-LEWIS: They're
well made.

00:55:55.155 --> 00:55:57.860
DAN GALPIN: HandyGames did a
brilliant job with that.

00:55:57.860 --> 00:55:59.880
You can see, even "Wild Blood,"
which is kind of small

00:55:59.880 --> 00:56:01.900
and low contrast, you
can still read it,

00:56:01.900 --> 00:56:03.960
even on this tablet.

00:56:03.960 --> 00:56:10.190
And that's an epic game too
in terms of its content.

00:56:10.190 --> 00:56:10.610
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's true.

00:56:10.610 --> 00:56:12.330
You will see a lot of
Gameloft games.

00:56:12.330 --> 00:56:15.670
You'll see a lot of Com2uS
games, a lot of EA games.

00:56:15.670 --> 00:56:19.620
There are big studios that
are well funded.

00:56:19.620 --> 00:56:26.380
So I guess the point is that,
I would say, maybe once a

00:56:26.380 --> 00:56:30.200
month, a game that we see from
our moderator page is good

00:56:30.200 --> 00:56:32.240
enough to get featured.

00:56:32.240 --> 00:56:35.570
So I wouldn't pin all
your hopes on it.

00:56:35.570 --> 00:56:39.900
But if you do want to be
reviewed on this show, the way

00:56:39.900 --> 00:56:43.650
to do it is to go to our
moderator page, which you'll

00:56:43.650 --> 00:56:46.450
have to search for because I
don't have the URL handy, but

00:56:46.450 --> 00:56:48.360
the Friday Review moderator.

00:56:48.360 --> 00:56:49.970
And just nominate it
for the date that

00:56:49.970 --> 00:56:50.610
you're interested in.

00:56:50.610 --> 00:56:51.620
And if it doesn't get
picked up that

00:56:51.620 --> 00:56:53.600
date, nominate it again.

00:56:53.600 --> 00:56:56.160
And if people aren't voting
for it, maybe

00:56:56.160 --> 00:56:57.770
ask yourself why.

00:56:57.770 --> 00:57:00.800
DAN GALPIN: I mean, looking at
the five games we have today,

00:57:00.800 --> 00:57:06.330
in terms of a combination of
graphical polish, gameplay,

00:57:06.330 --> 00:57:08.110
all of these different
elements--

00:57:08.110 --> 00:57:11.660
"Greedy Spiders," we featured
the original.

00:57:11.660 --> 00:57:13.490
We'll probably feature "Greedy
Spiders 2" as well.

00:57:15.990 --> 00:57:17.890
IAN NI-LEWIS: It's as good as
it was before or better.

00:57:17.890 --> 00:57:20.260
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, it's as good
as it was before or better.

00:57:20.260 --> 00:57:21.820
IAN NI-LEWIS: But that's
a really polished game.

00:57:21.820 --> 00:57:23.420
DAN GALPIN: It's a really,
really polished game.

00:57:23.420 --> 00:57:25.100
IAN NI-LEWIS: And you've got
to remember too, we would

00:57:25.100 --> 00:57:28.680
really, really love to believe
that featuring is something

00:57:28.680 --> 00:57:31.740
that we can just do for games
because they're awesome,

00:57:31.740 --> 00:57:33.570
because we really want to
support indie developers.

00:57:33.570 --> 00:57:35.860
It's not.

00:57:35.860 --> 00:57:38.360
The featuring process is
actually for filling our

00:57:38.360 --> 00:57:41.010
storefront and making
Google Play a more

00:57:41.010 --> 00:57:42.180
attractive place to be.

00:57:42.180 --> 00:57:44.060
DAN GALPIN: Well, we want to
make sure when people download

00:57:44.060 --> 00:57:46.450
something off the store that
they're happy with it.

00:57:46.450 --> 00:57:48.100
Because that's what gets
people going back.

00:57:48.100 --> 00:57:50.650
And that's what makes the
featuring process work.

00:57:50.650 --> 00:57:53.120
We want to make sure that when
we do have a great indie title

00:57:53.120 --> 00:57:54.860
that comes through
that we put it up

00:57:54.860 --> 00:57:56.080
there and it does something.

00:57:56.080 --> 00:57:58.485
IAN NI-LEWIS: So you know what's
really awesome, though,

00:57:58.485 --> 00:58:05.792
is what they've started to
do with collections.

00:58:05.792 --> 00:58:07.550
Because if you go in here--

00:58:07.550 --> 00:58:09.340
DAN GALPIN: In, like,
a tabletop games.

00:58:09.340 --> 00:58:12.760
IAN NI-LEWIS: OK, so Tavares
Ford, who's a buddy of ours,

00:58:12.760 --> 00:58:17.090
made this collection
of tabletop games.

00:58:17.090 --> 00:58:19.040
DAN GALPIN: It doesn't even
sound like a real name when

00:58:19.040 --> 00:58:19.580
you hear his name.

00:58:19.580 --> 00:58:20.260
IAN NI-LEWIS: I know, right?

00:58:20.260 --> 00:58:21.080
DAN GALPIN: It sounds
like a car.

00:58:21.080 --> 00:58:22.400
IAN NI-LEWIS: Ford Prefect
or something.

00:58:22.400 --> 00:58:22.980
DAN GALPIN: Exactly, exactly.

00:58:22.980 --> 00:58:25.480
He's actually part of
"Hitchhiker's Guide."

00:58:25.480 --> 00:58:25.860
IAN NI-LEWIS: I know.

00:58:25.860 --> 00:58:29.850
And it's weird too because one
of the guys that did WebGL on

00:58:29.850 --> 00:58:32.740
Chrome is named Gregg Tavares.

00:58:32.740 --> 00:58:36.010
And so it's like, everybody
always gets it mixed up.

00:58:36.010 --> 00:58:39.865
But there's a few things,
like, check this out.

00:58:39.865 --> 00:58:45.700
"Neuroshima Hex," we learned
about "Neuroshima Hex" from, I

00:58:45.700 --> 00:58:48.390
think, one of our
old co-workers--

00:58:48.390 --> 00:58:49.270
was it Chris?

00:58:49.270 --> 00:58:53.620
And we were super-unimpressed
at first.

00:58:53.620 --> 00:58:57.390
But then they did some updates,
and it actually

00:58:57.390 --> 00:58:58.560
started getting fun.

00:58:58.560 --> 00:59:00.077
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, I mean, look,
we even have "Rage of

00:59:00.077 --> 00:59:00.730
Bahamut" up there.

00:59:00.730 --> 00:59:03.400
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, "Rage of
Bahamut," I mean, you gotta

00:59:03.400 --> 00:59:04.480
toss in a ringer, I guess.

00:59:04.480 --> 00:59:08.890
But the point being, though,
that I think this is going to

00:59:08.890 --> 00:59:12.650
turn into a channel for
more attention.

00:59:12.650 --> 00:59:15.120
Because for instance, for
the longest time--

00:59:15.120 --> 00:59:17.030
DAN GALPIN: I was so excited
about the retro site.

00:59:17.030 --> 00:59:17.860
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, yeah.

00:59:17.860 --> 00:59:19.710
Because remember, for the
longest time, we'd get these

00:59:19.710 --> 00:59:20.670
